        {
            "title": "Master thesis: Modelling of sand transport in the surf zone",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 9,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2016
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 9,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2017
                }
            },
            "description": "For my master research project, I modelled the onshore sand transport in the surf zone during fair weather conditions under supervision of Huib de Swart and Gerben Ruessink. This project included a field campaign in Denmark in the autumn 2016. A sand transport model was built in Matlab and coupled to the hydrodynamic SWASH model. The coupled model was used to simulate the hydrodynamics and bed level change measured during the field campaign. The field data was partly used for model calibration and the rest of the data was used for model validation. The model results showed that the velocity skewness transport mechanism dominates over the velocity asymmetry mechanism and that the total transport is dominated by the onshore transport due to waves in the shoaling zone. However, it is recommended to improve the simulation of the current and the non-linearities in the sea surface elevation and wave velocity in the SWASH model to increase the accuracy of the model.",
